==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|abetten}}, {{m|enm|abette}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|abeter||to entice}}, from {{m|fro|a-||to}} + {{m|fro|beter||hound on, urge, to bait}}, from either {{etyl|dum|en}} {{m|dum|betan|bētan|incite}}, '''or''' from {{etyl|non|en}} {{m|non|beita||to cause to bite, bait, incite}}<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=2}}</ref>, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*baitijaną||to cause to bite}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*bʰeyd-||to split}}. Cognate with {{cog|is|beita||to set dogs on", "to feed}}.
* Alternate etymology traces the Middle English and Old French words through {{cog|ang|*ābǣtan||to hound on}}, from {{m|ang|ā-}} + {{m|ang|bǣtan||to bait}}, from the same {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} source.
* See also {{m|en|bait}}, {{m|en|bet}}.

