===Verb===
{{en-verb|abett}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete|transitive}} To [[urge]] on, [[stimulate]] (a person to do) something desirable. {{defdate|from end of 14th century to early 17th century}}<ref name=Chamber>{{R:CDOE|page=6}}</ref>
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[incite]]; to [[assist]] or [[encourage]] by aid or [[countenance]] in crime. {{defdate|from c. 1350-1470}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=4}}</ref>
#* '''2017''' September 27, David Browne, "[http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/hugh-hefner-playboy-founder-dead-at-91-w443922 Hugh Hefner, 'Playboy' Founder, Dead at 91]," ''Rolling Stone''
#*: By the early Seventies, Playboy was selling seven million copies a month and Hefner's globe-trotting lifestyle was '''abetted''' by his private jet, the Big Bunny, that contained a circular bed, an inside disco and a wet bar.
#* {{quote-book|year=1823|author=Ringan Gilhaize|title=The covenanters, by the author of Annals of the parish|passage=Those who would exalt themselves by '''abetting''' the strength of the Godless, and the wrength of the oppressors.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic}} To support, countenance, maintain, [[uphold]], or aid (any good cause, opinion, or action); to maintain. {{defdate|from late 16th century}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|year=1835|author=Jeremy Taylor|editor=George Rust|title=The whole works of the Right Rev. Jeremy Taylor|passage=Our duty is urged, and our confidence '''abetted'''.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To back up one's forecast of a doubtful issue, by staking money, etc., to [[bet]].

